content.description:
Nice moves on non-large positive holds. 

  Up the face, with a finish move lacking a positive foothold. 

warning: The rock on and around this route has not been climbed much yet, and much of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber - (and if possible, behind a large tree).

content.description:
Nice enough moves, but then getting all the way to the top is much harder. 

  Up the crack to its top, then stop and lower off. 

  Variation 1: Direct to top above the top of the crack (5.9+) 

  Variation 2: At the top of the crack, step up right and join the finish of the "Right Face" route. (5.6+) 

warning: The rock on and around this route has not been climbed much yet, and much of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber - (and if possible, behind a large tree).

content.description:
Lots of interesting outdoor moves. Very thoughtful crux, because need to alternate between looking and feeling. 

  Up the low arete to its top, then step left around the higher arete into a mini-dihedral (crux), then up that (more crux?) to the top. 

warning: The rock on and around this route has not been climbed much yet, and much of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber - (and if possible, behind a large tree).

content.description:
Everything slants, so if want to work on that, this delivers. Otherwise might just feel awkward. 

  . . (Wish this could be an arete climb, but no positive holds farther over on the right side). 

  Up the right face of the open book / dihedral, not using any holds on the left face.  

  Likely easier and less awkward if also use holds on the left face (but haven't tried that yet). 

warning: The rock on and around this route has not been climbed much yet, and much of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber - (and if possible, behind a large tree).

content.description:
Some thoughtful outdoor moves. More interesting and sustained if use the Middle Arete start (as did the First Ascent party). 

  Up onto the low platform, then the open book / dihedral above right, then the top open book / dihedral (crux). 

  Variation: Start up the narrow "sharp" fin / arete to the left of the low platform, then move over right to the first dihedral. 

warning: The rock on and around this route has not been climbed much yet, and much of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber - (and if possible, behind a large tree).

content.description:
Short wall with a high density of interesting moves. 

  Top-Rope: Access to top works by scrambling up around Right side. Trees and rocks can be used as natural anchors with static line or long slings. 

warning: The rock around this sector has not been climbed much yet, and much of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber.
